## Background and Significance

Redirects on Wikipedia serve as a crucial mechanism for maintaining the encyclopedia's usability and accessibility. When a page is moved or renamed, a redirect is created from the old title to the new one. This ensures that users who follow old links, whether from within Wikipedia or from external sources, are seamlessly directed to the correct article. The process of moving pages can occur for various reasons, including the need for more accurate or standardized naming conventions, disambiguation, or consolidation of related topics.

In the case of Ibn Khuzayma, the redirect ensures that any references to his name, whether in historical, theological, or biographical contexts, lead to the comprehensive article that details his life, works, and contributions. Ibn Khuzayma, also known as Abu Bakr Muhammad ibn Ishaq ibn Khuzayma, was a prominent [Sunni](/Sunni_Islam) [hadith](/Hadith) scholar and [jurist](/Fiqh) of the [Shafi'i](/Shafi'i) school. His most famous work, *Sahih Ibn Khuzayma*, is considered one of the significant collections of authentic hadiths in Islamic scholarship.

